{{nihongo|'''''Arabian'''''|アラビアン}} is a 1983 [[Arcade video game|arcade]] [[platform game]] developed and published by [[Sunsoft|Sun Electronics]] in Japan, and [[Atari, Inc.]] in North America.

The [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]] version was developed and released by Sunsoft only in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Super Arabian'''''|スーパーアラビアン}}.

==Gameplay==
''Arabian'' is a platform game where the player assumes the role of an adventurous [[Arabian]] prince whose goal is to rescue the princess from her palace. During his quest, the prince will sail seas, crawl through caves, and fly magic carpets.

==Release==
In magazine advertisements, ''Arabian'' was promoted by Eric Ginner, the world record holder for ''[[Millipede (video game)|Millipede]]'' and ''[[Liberator (video game)|Liberator]]'' at the time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arabian |url=https://www.pixelatedarcade.com/games/arabian |website=Pixelated Arcade}}</ref> Ginner later co-created the PlayStation game ''[[Gubble]]''.

== Reception ==
In Japan, ''Game Machine'' listed ''Arabian'' on their July 15, 1983 issue as being the fifth most-successful new table arcade unit of the month.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - テーブル型新製品 (New Videos-Table Type)|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=216|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=15 July 1983|page=37|lang=ja}}</ref> In the United States, it had sold at least 1,950 arcade cabinets by July 1983.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fujihara |first1=Mary |title=Inter Office Memo: Coin-Op Product Sales |url=http://www.atarigames.com/pdffiles/salesestimates1.pdf |publisher=[[Atari, Inc.]] |date=July 25, 1983 |access-date=14 October 2021 |archive-date=20 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211020200920/http://www.atarigames.com/pdffiles/salesestimates1.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Legacy==
''Super Arabian'' was re-released in a two-in-one [[PlayStation (console)|Sony PlayStation]] game, ''Memorial Series Sunsoft Vol.1'', which also included ''[[Ikki (video game)|Ikki]]''. ''Super Arabian'' is one of the video games was adapted by Manga titled {{nihongo|''[[Susume!! Seigaku Dennou Kenkyuubu]]''|進め！！静学電脳研究部|Shiawase no katachi}}, published in the Gamest Comics collection from April 1999.

''Tales of the Arabian Nights'' by [[Interceptor Micros|Interceptor Software]] had many similarities to ''Arabian''. It was published in 1984/5 for the [[Acorn Electron]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[BBC Micro]], [[Commodore 64]], and [[ZX Spectrum]].
 
The game was re-released for the [[Nintendo Switch]] by [[Hamster Corporation]] as part of the ''[[Arcade Archives]]'' series in October 2020.<ref>[https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/arcade-archives-arabian-switch/ Arcade Archives ARABIAN] nintendo.com</ref> The Famicom version of the game was also re-released as part the ''Sunsoft Collection 1'' compilation cartridge for the [[Evercade]] in September 2023.

